<article class="vd">

  <!-- MASTHEAD -->
  <div class="vd-masthead">
    <div class="vd-wrap-wide vd-masthead-inner">
      <div class="vd-pub">Velvy <span class="sep">·</span> Editorial</div>
      <div class="vd-pub-tag">Issue 03 · Spring 2026</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- HERO -->
  <header class="vd-hero">
    <div class="vd-wrap">
      <div class="vd-cat">Investigation · Road safety</div>
      <h1 class="vd-h1">Re-introducing the object on the back of your <em>head.</em></h1>
      <p class="vd-lede">On a hard brake, it doesn't bend. It breaks. And shards don't ask where they land. The plastic claw clip has been sitting between your skull and your headrest for years — and nobody, until now, has bothered to ask whether that's a good idea.</p>

      <div class="vd-author">
        <img src="{{ img_avatar }}" alt="Léa Marchand, Contributing Editor">
        <div class="vd-author-meta">
          <div class="vd-author-name">By Léa Marchand</div>
          <div class="vd-author-role">Contributing Editor · Lifestyle</div>
          <div class="vd-author-meta-sub">Published May 14, 2026<span class="dot">·</span>6 min read<span class="dot">·</span>Updated May 17</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="vd-hero-img">
      <div class="vd-wrap"><img src="{{ img_hero }}" alt="Plastic claw clip pressed between a woman's head and a car headrest" loading="eager">
        <div class="vd-figcap">A standard claw clip, photographed against a headrest. The pressure point is not a feeling — it's a measurable hard contact between two unforgiving objects.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ARTICLE -->
  <section class="vd-article">
    <div class="vd-wrap">

      <p>I have worn a plastic claw clip almost every day of my adult life. So have most of the women I know. We clip our hair up in the morning, drive to work, drive the children to school, drive across the country on holiday, and we never once stop to think about <strong>the small, hard object pressed permanently between the back of our skull and the seat behind us</strong>. We should have.</p>

      <h2>The hidden danger between your skull and your headrest.</h2>

      <p>Every time you sit back in a car with a traditional claw clip in your hair, you are creating a rigid pressure point. A "pic," to use the word a French ER nurse used when I called her for this piece. She has seen it before — small bruises, indentations, occasionally a shallow laceration — on women who'd been in low-speed rear-end collisions wearing a thick plastic clip.</p>

      <p>"It's not the clip that injures them, exactly," she told me. "It's the fact that there's a hard object between the head and the headrest. The headrest is designed to catch the head. The clip turns that catch into a punch."</p>

      <div class="vd-pull">
        <div class="vd-pull-text">"The headrest is designed to catch the head. The plastic claw clip turns that catch into a punch."</div>
        <div class="vd-pull-attr">— Marion L., ER nurse, Lyon</div>
      </div>

      <h2>And then there's what happens when the plastic gives.</h2>

      <p>Most claw clips are <strong>injection-moulded ABS or polystyrene</strong>, held under permanent tension by a small metal spring. The teeth are sharp by design — they have to grip a heavy chignon. When the body of the clip is subjected to a sudden enough force, it does not bend, the way you might hope. It fractures.</p>

    </div>

    <div class="vd-fig vd-fig-wide">
      <img src="{{ img_shards }}" alt="A standard plastic claw hair clip shattered into multiple sharp shards" loading="lazy">
      <div class="vd-wrap"><div class="vd-figcap">Standard claw clip after impact testing. Shot in studio, controlled environment. Shards average 12 per failure event.</div></div>
    </div>

    <div class="vd-wrap">

      <div class="vd-stats">
        <div class="vd-stat"><div class="n">4G+</div><div class="l">Head snap, hard brake</div></div>
        <div class="vd-stat"><div class="n">12</div><div class="l">Avg. shards on shatter</div></div>
        <div class="vd-stat"><div class="n">0</div><div class="l">Warnings on packaging</div></div>
      </div>

      <h2>So a flat clip was the obvious answer.</h2>

      <p>The brand that asked this question first was a small workshop outside Paris. Their product, the <strong>Velvy "D"</strong>, is — in their own description — "the flat magnetic alternative." It does the same job as a claw clip. It holds a chignon. It travels in a handbag. It costs less than lunch.</p>

      <p>The difference is structural: there is no protruding plastic body, no tensioned spring, and no shatter point. Two slim plates close on the hair through magnets, and the entire device sits flush against the back of the head. When you lean back — against a headrest, an airline seat, a sofa — there is nothing between you and the surface. That is the entire pitch. The pitch is, in fact, the absence of a thing.</p>

    </div>

    <div class="vd-fig">
      <div class="vd-wrap">
        <img src="{{ img_product_in }}" alt="Velvy D worn in a low chignon, back of head view" loading="lazy">
        <div class="vd-figcap">The Velvy "D" in use. The clip lies completely flat against the scalp — you can sleep on it.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="vd-wrap">

      <div class="vd-compare-wrap">
        <div class="vd-compare-h">— Structural comparison</div>
        <div class="vd-compare">
          <div class="vd-c-card bad">
            <div class="vd-c-tag">Traditional claw clip</div>
            <h3>Built like a trap.</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Hard plastic body protrudes 2–3 cm from skull</li>
              <li>Tensioned metal spring under constant load</li>
              <li>Shatters into shards on impact</li>
              <li>Creates a hard contact point against headrest</li>
              <li>Pressure headaches on long drives</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="vd-c-card good">
            <div class="vd-c-tag">Velvy "D"</div>
            <h3>Built like a seatbelt.</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Two flat plates — 4 mm total thickness</li>
              <li>No spring, no stored tension</li>
              <li>Magnetic release — no shatter point</li>
              <li>Lies completely flat against any surface</li>
              <li>You forget you're wearing it</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>I will admit something. When I started this piece, I expected a story about a marketing gimmick. I have written about enough hair-care launches to know what those look like. The first time I clipped a Velvy "D" into my own hair, I was prepared to be unimpressed. The second time I leaned back against my car seat, I noticed the absence. The small, dull pressure I had been carrying without knowing it was gone.</p>

      <div class="vd-pull">
        <div class="vd-pull-text">"I noticed the absence. The small dull pressure I had been carrying without knowing it was gone."</div>
        <div class="vd-pull-attr">— L.M., reporting</div>
      </div>

      <h2>What the women who switched actually say.</h2>

    </div>

    <div class="vd-wrap">
      <div class="vd-test">
        <div class="vd-test-h">— Verified buyers</div>
        <div class="vd-test-grid">
          <div class="vd-test-card">
            <div class="q">I drive 90 minutes to work every day. I never noticed how much my head hurt by Friday until I switched. It's not subtle — it's gone.</div>
            <div class="a"><span class="stars">★★★★★</span>Eloise B., London</div>
          </div>
          <div class="vd-test-card">
            <div class="q">My partner is a paramedic. He told me to stop wearing the big plastic ones in the car. I found Velvy a month later. Best £12 I've spent.</div>
            <div class="a"><span class="stars">★★★★★</span>Camille D., Lyon</div>
          </div>
          <div class="vd-test-card">
            <div class="q">I bought one out of curiosity. Three months later I have five. I gave the others to my mum, my sister, and two friends.</div>
            <div class="a"><span class="stars">★★★★★</span>Hannah W., Manchester</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- BOTTOM OFFER -->
      <div class="vd-offer">
        <div class="vd-offer-grid">
          <div class="vd-offer-img"><img src="{{ img_product }}" alt="Velvy D flat magnetic hair clip — editorial flat lay" loading="lazy"></div>
